## 3. Parameter Selection

Before using RQA, three parameters must be estimated: the time delay (τ), 
the embedding dimension (M), and the recurrence radius.

### 3.1 Time Delay : Average Mutual Information (AMI)

The optimal time delay τ was estimated using the Average Mutual Information 
function. The first local minimum of AMI shows the lag at which consecutive 
embedded coordinates become as independent as possible, which gives the best reconstruction of the
attractor.

![AMI](fig_ami.png)

*Figure 2. Average Mutual Information as a function of lag. The first local 
minimum occurs at τ = 4 days.*

The AMI function reached its first local minimum at **τ = 4 days**. This makes 
physical sense — pollution episodes in Beijing typically last 3–5 days before 
wind or rain disperses the accumulated particulate matter.

### 3.2 Embedding Dimension — False Nearest Neighbors (FNN)

The False Nearest Neighbors method identifies the minimum number of dimensions 
needed so that nearby points in phase space remain true neighbors rather than 
becoming artificially close due to projection from a lower-dimensional space.

![FNN](fig_fnn.png)

*Figure 3. False Nearest Neighbors percentage as a function of embedding 
dimension. FNN drops below 5% at M = 4.*

FNN dropped below the 5% threshold at **M = 4**, meaning four delayed copies 
of the PM2.5 signal are required to fully unfold its attractor. At M = 1 and 
M = 2, over 60% of neighbors were false — confirming the signal was severely 
under-embedded in lower dimensions.

### 3.3 Radius Selection

Following the recommended 2–5% recurrence range for environmental signals, a 
binary search was used to find the radius producing approximately 3% recurrence.

**Table 2. Final RQA parameters**

| Parameter | Value | Method |
|---|---|---|
| Delay (τ) | 4 days | AMI first local minimum |
| Embedding dimension (M) | 4 | FNN below 5% threshold |
| Radius | 0.7897 | Binary search targeting ~3% recurrence |
| Actual %REC | 3.05% | Verification |

