## 4. RQA — PM2.5 Auto-Recurrence

### 4.1 Recurrence Plot

![Recurrence Plot](fig_recurrence_plot.png)

*Figure 4. Recurrence plot of PM2.5 (τ=4, M=4, radius=0.7897). Diagonal 
line structures indicate repeated trajectories. Annual block patterns reflect 
the seasonal cycle.*

The recurrence plot shows clear diagonal line structures running parallel to 
the main diagonal, indicating that PM2.5 repeatedly follows similar trajectories 
over time. The periodic block pattern — repeating approximately every 365 days — 
reflects the annual seasonal cycle. Denser clusters around 2011 and 2013 
correspond to severe winter pollution episodes.

### 4.2 RQA Measures

![RQA Results](fig_rqa_results.png)

*Figure 5. RQA measures for PM2.5.*

**Table 3. RQA results**

| Measure | Value | Interpretation |
|---|---|---|
| %REC | 3.05% | System returns to prior states at a structured rate |
| %DET | 16.74% | Moderate determinism — trajectories partly predictable |
| maxL | 11 days | Longest consistent trajectory lasts 11 days |
| L | 2.13 days | Average diagonal line length |
| ENTR | 0.39 | Low complexity — mostly short recurrent episodes |
| %LAM | 32.64% | System gets trapped in sustained states frequently |
| TT | 2.28 days | Average trapping time per pollution episode |

The most diagnostic finding is that **%LAM (32.64%) is nearly double %DET 
(16.74%)**. PM2.5 gets trapped in elevated or depressed states more than it 
follows structured trajectories — consistent with pollution episodes that are 
sticky but not highly predictable in their onset.

