## 5. CRQA — PM2.5 × Temperature

Cross-Recurrence Quantification Analysis examines whether the state of PM2.5 
at time *i* is close to the state of temperature at time *j*, revealing the 
degree of dynamic coupling between the two variables.

### 5.1 Cross-Recurrence Plot

![CRQA Plot](fig_crqa_plot.png)

*Figure 6. Left: RQA recurrence plot (PM2.5 vs itself). Right: CRQA 
cross-recurrence plot (PM2.5 × temperature). The banded structure in CRQA 
reflects seasonal coupling.*

The cross-recurrence plot looks strikingly different from the auto-recurrence 
plot. A clear horizontal band appears along the bottom, and the middle regions 
are sparse. This banded pattern reflects the anti-phase seasonal relationship — 
PM2.5 peaks in winter exactly when temperature is lowest, so they only share 
similar states at seasonal extremes.

### 5.2 RQA vs CRQA Comparison

![RQA vs CRQA](fig_rqa_vs_crqa.png)

*Figure 7. Bar chart comparison of RQA and CRQA measures.*

**Table 4. RQA vs CRQA comparison**

| Measure | RQA (PM2.5) | CRQA (PM2.5×Temp) | Difference |
|---|---|---|---|
| %REC | 3.05% | 2.28% | -0.77 |
| %DET | 16.74% | **34.56%** | +17.82 |
| maxL | 11 | **16** | +5 |
| ENTR | 0.39 | 0.72 | +0.33 |
| %LAM | 32.64% | 37.52% | +4.88 |
| TT | 2.28 | 2.36 | +0.08 |

The most surprising finding is that **%DET is more than double in CRQA 
(34.56% vs 16.74%)**. When PM2.5 and temperature share similar states, those 
shared states form longer, more structured diagonal lines — reflecting the 
strong seasonal forcing that drives both variables into predictable joint 
trajectories during winter.

