## 6. DCRP — Leader-Follower Analysis

The Diagonal Cross-Recurrence Profile sweeps across lags from -60 to +60 days, 
measuring recurrence rate along each diagonal. This reveals whether one variable 
consistently leads the other in time.

![DCRP](fig_dcrp.png)

*Figure 8. Diagonal Cross-Recurrence Profile. Peak at lag = +47 days indicates 
temperature leads PM2.5 by approximately 47 days.*

The DCRP shows a clear peak at **lag = +47 days**, meaning temperature changes 
precede PM2.5 changes by approximately 6–7 weeks. Recurrence is lowest near 
lag = 0, meaning the two variables are least dynamically similar simultaneously. 
This makes meteorological sense: autumn temperatures drop in October, atmospheric 
inversion conditions build over the following weeks, and PM2.5 peaks arrive in 
December — roughly 47 days later.

**Temperature is the leading variable in this coupled system.**

