## 7. Windowed RQA — Dynamics Over Time

RQA was applied in sliding 90-day windows with 30-day steps, producing a time 
series of RQA measures that reveals epochs of high or low regularity.

![Windowed RQA](fig_windowed_rqa.png)

*Figure 9. Windowed RQA showing %REC, %DET, and %LAM over time. Red shaded 
region marks the 2013 pollution event.*

Three important findings emerge from the windowed analysis:

**%REC** drops to nearly zero at the start of 2013 — the system briefly entered 
completely novel states — then spikes to its highest value in the entire 5-year 
period (~14%). This marks the 2013 Beijing pollution event as a genuine dynamical 
transition.

**%DET** reveals that the 2011 winter was the most deterministic period (~42%), 
meaning pollution trajectories were more predictable that year than any other. 
This varies substantially across years, confirming that determinism is not stable 
over time.

**%LAM** reaches its maximum in 2011 winter (~60%), confirming that pollution 
episodes were most sustained during that period. The near-zero drop at early 2013 
followed by a sharp recovery shows that the extreme event broke existing recurrence 
patterns before establishing new ones.

