## 9. Comparison of All Three Methods

![All Methods Comparison](fig_all_methods_comparison.png)

*Figure 11. Complete comparison of RQA, CRQA, and mdRQA measures.*

**Table 5. Final results summary — all three methods**

| Measure | RQA (PM2.5) | CRQA (PM2.5×Temp) | mdRQA (All 4) |
|---|---|---|---|
| %REC | 3.05% | 2.28% | 3.18% |
| %DET | 16.74% | 34.56% | **40.73%** |
| maxL | 11 | 16 | 12 |
| ENTR | 0.39 | 0.72 | **0.82** |
| %LAM | 32.64% | 37.52% | **55.06%** |
| TT | 2.28 | 2.36 | 2.66 |

The clear pattern is that **determinism and laminarity increase with every 
additional dimension**. PM2.5 alone appears mostly irregular (%DET = 16.74%), 
but embedded in its full atmospheric context the system is highly organised 
(%DET = 40.73%). The %LAM nearly doubles from RQA to mdRQA (32.64% → 55.06%), 
indicating that the complete atmospheric system gets trapped in sustained states 
far more than any single variable suggests.

