## 10. Parameter Sensitivity

![Sensitivity](fig_sensitivity.png)

*Figure 12. Sensitivity of RQA measures to changes in radius. The chosen 
radius (red dashed line) sits in the stable lower region of all curves.*

All three measures increase monotonically with radius, as expected. Crucially, 
the relative ordering and interpretation of results remain stable across a range 
of radius values around the chosen threshold of 0.7897. The findings are robust 
and not artifacts of the specific parameter chosen.

---

## 11. Conclusion

Applying RQA-based methods to the Beijing PM2.5 dataset reveals a dynamically 
structured signal with meaningful recurrence properties:

- PM2.5 shows moderate determinism (%DET = 16.74%) and high laminarity 
(%LAM = 32.64%), with typical trapping times of ~2 days
- CRQA reveals that PM2.5–temperature coupling is seasonally driven and more 
deterministic than PM2.5 alone (%DET = 34.56%)
- The DCRP identifies temperature as the leading variable, preceding PM2.5 
changes by ~47 days
- Windowed RQA shows the 2013 Beijing pollution event as a genuine dynamical 
transition — all three measures drop to near zero then spike to new highs
- mdRQA reveals the full atmospheric system is far more deterministic 
(%DET = 40.73%) and laminar (%LAM = 55.06%) than any single variable
- Parameter sensitivity confirms all findings are robust to changes in radius

